# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1874-chicago-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] The **Baltimore Canaries** played their final season in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 9–38.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 22–33.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] The Hartford Dark Blues were formed by Morgan Bulkeley and joined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1874 season.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] They finished in seventh place in their debut.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1874-chicago-white-stockings-season/1874-new-york-mutuals-season] The New York Mutuals baseball team finished second in the National Association in 1874.
